tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One of the main problems in finance is the princip=
al-agent problem, and one of the main forms that it takes is steak dinners.=
 You are selling a product, and you want someone to buy it. The person maki=
ng the buying=C2=A0decision=C2=A0is not necessarily the person paying for t=
he product, or the person who will benefit if it=E2=80=99s good or suffer i=
f it=E2=80=99s bad. If you are an investment banker, you are selling financ=
ial services to a corporation, but the corporation=E2=80=99s decisions are =
made by a person =E2=80=94=C2=A0perhaps the chief executive officer, perhap=
s the assistant treasurer =E2=80=94=C2=A0and she likes steak. If you take h=
er out to a nice dinner, maybe she will buy your financial services, even i=
f your competitors offer better services at a lower price. She has a fiduci=
ary duty to her company to get the best deal for shareholders, but she real=
ly=C2=A0likes steak. The value of the services, and their cost, accrue to t=
he corporation and its shareholders; the steak accrues to the assistant tre=
asurer.</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I say =E2=80=9Csteak dinners=E2=80=
=9D because steak dinners =E2=80=94=C2=A0and tickets to sporting events, an=
d fancy conferences in nice locations =E2=80=94=C2=A0are the standard curre=
ncy for this sort of thing, because the more obvious currency =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0money =E2=80=94=C2=A0is off limits. If you went to the assistant treasur=
er of a company and said =E2=80=9Cyour company should pay my bank $10 milli=
on to do stock buybacks, and in exchange I=E2=80=99ll hand you this briefca=
se with $1 million in it,=E2=80=9D that would be bad. That would be a=C2=A0=
<em>bribe</em>, and you and she would get in trouble for it. That is a very=
 <em>clear </em>violation of her duty to her company. The steak dinners are=
 not. =E2=80=9CI met with investment bankers to discuss value-added strateg=
ies for doing stock buybacks,=E2=80=9D she can say, =E2=80=9Cand the meetin=
g happened to occur at a convenient time (dinner) and place (steakhouse).=
=E2=80=9D Nothing untoward about that. She was a good fiduciary for her com=
pany; she was just trying to get information and do due diligence and learn=
 things; her loyalty to shareholders could not be overcome by a mere steak =
dinner. Even if the wine was also nice.</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Th=
ere is a certain amount of possible boundary-pushing. What if the wine is=
=C2=A0<em>really </em>nice=3F What if you send the assistant treasurer home=
 with some extra steaks for her family=3F What if you just ship a case of w=
ine to her house=3F What if you take her to a sporting event and=C2=A0<em>d=
on=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>discuss business=3F What if you send her and her fri=
ends to the sporting event without you=3F=C2=A0</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16p=
