x 0;">A problem for many startup founders is that they are rich on paper, b=
ut don=E2=80=99t have any money. You start a company, things are going well=
, investors keep investing in your company at high valuations, and your sta=
ke is worth tens or hundreds of millions of dollars. But you are a startup =
founder so you don=E2=80=99t take a big salary, and you don=E2=80=99t have =
much actual cash to spend. You can=E2=80=99t live a lifestyle that matches =
your centimillionaire status.=C2=A0</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">How do=
 you turn your equity into cash=3F The most traditional answer is that you =
do an initial public offering of your company: That transforms your illiqui=
d hard-to-value stake in a startup into liquid shares of a public company, =
and those are easy to turn into cash. (Most straightforwardly, you can sell=
 some of them, or if you don=E2=80=99t want to do that you can use the shar=
es as collateral for a margin loan.)</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That=
=E2=80=99s the traditional approach, but it is not available to everyone. A=
n IPO is complicated and expensive, and these days companies often stay pri=
vate for quite a long time; you might not want to wait many years before ca=
shing out. Also, I mean, if your startup is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0a fraud, or frau=
d-adjacent, or otherwise rickety,=C2=A0it might have a hard time doing an I=
PO. And you will particularly=C2=A0<em>want=C2=A0</em>to cash our your shar=
es if your company is a fraud.</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So there ar=
e other, non-IPO approaches. You might find private investors who are willi=
ng to buy some of your shares, either in a straight sale or as part of your=
 company=E2=80=99s fundraising round. (This used to be frowned upon =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0venture capitalists wanted founders to wait until the IPO to take =
money off the table =E2=80=94=C2=A0but is more common now that companies st=
ay private longer.)=C2=A0</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or you can borro=
w against your stock. =E2=80=9CLook, I have $100 million of hot startup sto=
ck,=E2=80=9D you could tell a bank or other lender; =E2=80=9Ccan you lend m=
e $50 million against it=3F If I don=E2=80=99t pay you back, you can keep t=
he stock.=E2=80=9D The lender might say yes. It might do some due diligence=
 on your company and decide that your stock will definitely be worth at lea=
st $100 million, so lending you $50 million is pretty safe. It might think =
that lending you the money will help it win the mandate to lead your compan=
y=E2=80=99s IPO in a year or two, which pays well and is prestigious.<a hre=
f=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inl=
ine-block;"> <span>[1]</span> </a>=C2=A0</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">B=
ut that=E2=80=99s a pretty big risk for the bank: It=E2=80=99s lending mone=
y against risky collateral, startup equity that could easily go to zero. Un=
like in a public-company margin loan, there=E2=80=99s not really any way fo=
r the bank to hedge: If the business starts to deteriorate, the bank can=E2=
=80=99t seize your stock and sell it, because the stock isn=E2=80=99t publi=
c and there=E2=80=99s no way to sell it.=C2=A0</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">Ah but what if you could=C2=A0<em>pre</em>-sell it=3F What if you came=
 to the bank and said: =E2=80=9CI would like to borrow $50 million from you=
. As collateral, I have this stock that is worth $100 million, based on th=
e valuation in our last funding round. I think it is=C2=A0<em>really=C2=A0<=
/em>worth much more, because I think my company will be great. But you migh=
t disagree, that=E2=80=99s fine. But I have a friend here =E2=80=94=C2=A0on=
e of the investors in my company =E2=80=94=C2=A0who shares my belief in the=
 company, and who also has a lot of money, unlike me. He=E2=80=99s willing =
to write me a=C2=A0<em>put</em>, or rather, he=E2=80=99s willing to write <=
em>you </em>a put. He will promise you that, if anything goes wrong and you=
 have to foreclose on my stock, he=E2=80=99ll buy it from you for $50 milli=
on. So you are totally safe: If things work out well, the stock will be wor=
th much more than $100 million, and I will easily pay back your $50 million=
 with interest. If things go south, though, you can always sell the stock t=
o my friend for $50 million, so your $50 million loan to me is safe.=E2=80=
=9D<a href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; dis=
play: inline-block;"> <span>[2]</span> </a></p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;=
">Is that convincing=3F Well, maybe; who=E2=80=99s your friend=3F If that p=
